nodes.bodyText:
If this is true, is there any penalty for writing a callback which consumes one result at a time and returns CONTINUE? (No usage of while(true) to consume everything in the resultset).
Something like:
    public CallbackResponse cursorReady(AsyncResultSet rs) {
      switch(rs.tryNext()) {
        case OK:
          System.out.println(rs.getRow());
          return CallbackResponse.CONTINUE;
        case NOT_READY:
          return CallbackResponse.CONTINUE;
      }
      return CallbackResponse.DONE;
    }

I find this more intuitive than trying to remember that the resultset might have multiple rows of available data that should be consumed before calling CONTINUE. Curious what your thoughts are.

